  "local_port": 50722,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Minecraft: How do you re-generate chunks with MCEdit?",
  "response": "Regenerating chunks in Minecraft using MCEdit involves using the tool to delete unwanted chunks so that they regenerate when you reload the world in Minecraft. Here's a step-by-step guide on how to do this:\n\n1. **Backup Your World**: Before making any modifications, always create a backup of your Minecraft world. This prevents data loss in case something goes wrong.\n\n2. **Download and Install MCEdit**: Ensure you have MCEdit installed on your computer. It's a third-party program, so you might need to search for a legacy version since official support and updates may have ceased.\n\n3. **Open Your World in MCEdit**:\n   - Launch MCEdit.\n   - Click on \"Open\" and select your Minecraft world from the list.\n   - MCEdit will load the world and display it in a 3D visual format.\n\n4. **Navigate to the Chunks to Regenerate**:\n   - Use the navigation controls to move around your world until you find the area you want to regenerate.\n   - This will usually be an area where you want to see new features or biomes introduced in subsequent updates.\n\n5. **Select Chunks to Delete**:\n   - Use the selection tool to outline the chunks you wish to delete. You can adjust the selection size to encompass full chunks.\n   - It's often easiest to work at the chunk level, which is a 16x16 area.\n\n6. **Delete the Selected Chunks**:\n   - Once you have selected the chunks, press the \"Delete\" key or find the delete option in the menu to remove them entirely from your world.\n   - Remember, deleting chunks removes all blocks and entities within them.\n\n7. **Save Your Changes**:\n   - Once you have deleted the selected chunks, save the changes. MCEdit may take some time to save large edits.\n   - Exit MCEdit once saving is complete.\n\n8. **Reload the World in Minecraft**:\n   - Open Minecraft and load your world.\n   - The deleted chunks will regenerate using the current world seed and version of the game, allowing new terrain and structures based on the latest updates to appear.\n\n9. **Verify the Changes**:\n   - Explore the newly generated areas to ensure the changes were applied correctly.\n   - Check if new features or biomes are present, confirming the regeneration process.\n\nBy following these steps, you should be able to regenerate chunks in Minecraft using MCEdit. Be cautious with the areas you delete and always test in a backup world if you are unsure of how your changes will affect the world.",
